title: ICE with GAT, TAIT + async{} when missing bound in the GAT.

labels.name: I-ICE
labels.description: Issue: The compiler panicked, giving an Internal Compilation Error (ICE) ❄️

labels.name: E-needs-test
labels.description: Call for participation: writing correctness tests

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

labels.name: E-needs-mcve
labels.description: Call for participation: This issue needs a Minimal Complete and Verifiable Example

labels.name: GATs-triaged
labels.description: Issues using the `generic_associated_types` feature that have been triaged

body:
### Code I think the cause is the code is incorrect: FooFuture should require `where B: Bar`. It doesn't, somehow the compiler doesn't catch this, and then ICEs at codegen if you try to use `FooFuture` because u32 is not Bar. ```Rust #![feature(generic_associated_types)] #![feature(type_alias_impl_trait)] use futures::executor::block_on; use std::future::Future; trait Bar { fn bar(&self); } trait Foo { type FooFuture<'a, B>: Future + 'a where B: 'a, Self: 'a; fn foo<'a, B: Bar>(&'a self, bar: &'a B) -> Self::FooFuture<'_, B>; } struct MyFoo; impl Foo for MyFoo { type FooFuture<'a, B> where B: 'a, Self: 'a, = impl Future + 'a; fn foo<'a, B: Bar>(&'a self, bar: &'a B) -> Self::FooFuture<'_, B> { async move { bar.bar(); } } } fn main() { let boom: ::FooFuture<'static, u32> = unsafe { core::mem::zeroed() }; block_on(boom); } ``` [playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=ab2665ecb8cdfff050dcf2ef6bf86039) ### Meta `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` version: 1.58.0-nightly (2021-10-28 c390d69a615f095208ac) ``` ### Error output ``` error: internal compiler error: Encountered error `Unimplemented` selecting `Binder(, [])` during codegen ```
